segments.text: inevitable decision.
First, as an educational institution, I think it was proper that a young man in this country that wanted to go to college, and particularly right out of high school, if he didn't want to enter
military training at that particular time.
I don't think it should be forced on them.
This, to me, serves a little bit to be like a dictatorship.
There are some people that will never be military people.
Let's recognize it.
Everybody can't be an engineer.
Everybody can't be a general.
Everybody can't be a doctor.
Some people are born to be military, and they're going to be.
I just think it's right.
You have a choice, and that's the basis of our country.
Free enterprise isn't a democracy.
Choice, you have freedom of choice.
Okay, how about allowing women to go there for the first time?
I definitely agree with that.
As a matter of fact, let's talk about that a minute.
I'm glad you asked this question.
What was the expression you used when you asked me a question a few moments ago about the attitude of some civilians that you call a military mentality?
I think that to have a school set up as we have in the past for men only, this is part of the
the concept you're talking about, military, and I told you it had changed.
Look at all the academies now.
Sure.
Look at the increased recruiting of women.
Sure.
Incredible.
And furthermore, what's wrong?
God made men and women to communicate and live together.
What's wrong with this?
I think it's great.
Furthermore, it's only natural at an educational institution now to learn to live with a woman as a kid, as a youngster, as a teenager, as a young man.
It's only natural.
Now, when you're talking about recruiting women in the armed forces, this is a different question.
I know it's a different question, and let's shift to that now.
You favor the switch of women to A&M.
Now, do you favor increasing the number of women in the Air Force?

I think we've just about, in time of peace, and even planning for military organization, you know, a 100% man unit that's supposed to be conceived as an outfit ready to go to combat, I think we've just about approached the point of the percentage of women in the armed forces.
As a matter of fact, it's already being, it's coming to the surface.
There's many current
officers say of colonel nature that much much younger than I and a lot of my advantage that already they see the limitations.
We've almost exceeded limitations.
To try to and look at the legislation that's begun to bubble.
Limitations to try to what?
To limitations to be applied to women where they shouldn't be in combat.
This is wrong.
Wait a minute.
You think I'm confused.
You think

that allowing women into the service is right, but you feel, and I don't know if I'm putting words in your mouth, but just for clarification, you think allowing women into the service is right, but allowing, but having women participate in combat is wrong.
That's right.
They have a, again, let's go back to leadership.
What did I say?
Putting people in positions in accordance with their weaknesses and strengths.
Okay.
You're not going to put women in the front line of a professional football team, are you?
Why don't we recruit them and put them in there?
That's foolish.
I've been in the infantry.
I've been in the artillery.
I've been in fighter airplanes.
Actually, I know in Russia, in Russia, they actually use some women in fighter airplanes at the front.
But this was in wartime when a country was fighting for its life and had over a generation of people, young people killed in that.
nation.
20 million people killed in World War II.
They had to use people.
Now we use women as transport pilots and ferrying aircraft in World War II and turned out great, but that's a support role.
Women can do some jobs in support roles, in my opinion, better than men.
Let's use them there.
Let's use them in support roles, but let's don't ever
until that, you know, we're about ready to lose our nation.
Let's don't plan on using women in combat.
I agree.
You've heard of General Senglob, who was recalled from Korea and practically fired by President Carter.
Oh, yeah.
I knew him as a colonel in Southeast Asia.
And I agree with him that women in combat, as a matter of fact, the extent that we visualize eventually increasing percentage of women in armed forces, I think
deserves a new look.
And here again, you know, I said that the armed forces reflect the culture and the characteristics of our civilian population.
Look at the duplication of soldiers you have to make to treat women the way we in America are taught to treat women.
Ladies and gentlemen, look at the duplication of soldiers you have to have.
There's just many reasons.
In times of emergency,
That's a different thing.
Yeah, but in the general peacetime services, you think mostly their role should be one of support.
I definitely agree.
As a matter of fact, even further, I don't know whether you get to this or not, but I've been doing a lot of thinking about the draft.
And, you know, even the courts got involved in this.
Sure.
The Congress is involved in it.
We're almost at the point where we're trying to legislate social life.
I definitely, I believe in the draft.
Okay, you believe in the draft.
Oh yeah, there's no doubt about it.
Matter of fact, I think it's the old American tradition and culture that the American man has a responsibility toward his country.
This is the basis of patriotism.
and I believe it's still there.
What about drafting women?
That's the point I'm going to make.
I don't think the number of women that I foresee being in the armed forces and the role they'll play, I don't think that it's necessary to lay on a draft for women.
But I think and respect the women and the men of this country equally alike, and I think that in time of emergency, you'll have enough
young women that are ready to volunteer to fill their quota in the armed forces.
I don't think you have the problem.
And also, in the support role, generally speaking, it doesn't take as much time to train people in that role.
To train a combat pilot, that takes time.
Also, to train a crack maintenance man, electronic equipment, this takes time.
Now, some women can do that.
But generally speaking, the proportion of women
that, let's say, we'd have to get in the service in time of emergency.
I think that wouldn't be so critical, but now, men, that's a different thing.
You've got to get the men aboard.
We should have a draft.
I definitely agree.
Okay, now, during the time that you were in the military, of course, they integrated the services.
Truman issued, I think it was Executive Order 9066 in 1947, integrating
desegregating the armed forces.
What was your opinion on that?
Desegregation.
Sure.
Integrated units.
I think that the desegregation and the elimination of what we consider the minority in this country, the armed forces should be patted on the back and complimented from a standpoint of human rights
in being the forerunner of this.
Maybe, let's say by edict, they had to do it, of course.
But I think it was a great idea.
I think the Armed Forces was far ahead of the civilians of this nation, of this country, in this area, that they're not comfortable.
Okay, and...
I'm all for it.
And during your term, or your career in the service, did you have any racial problems that you remember
You're sitting here in charge of the 12th in 1967 and 1968, and these were pretty hot times in the cities, and there were black riots in the cities.
Did you have any racial problems at all?
I don't remember, and I must have to think a few minutes.
I don't remember having one single racial problem, frankly, in my entire military career.
In your entire military career?
I don't remember.
Now, I've read of them.
I certainly read of them, you know, about them in the South Asian War and overseas.
I read of them recently on board naval vessels at sea.
I've read about these and again, I go back to my statement.
The Armed Forces reflect the culture and nature and characteristics of civilians.
It's certainly in worse than it is in civilian, but
I think if you have a tendency to have these types of problems in the civilian world, in the United States, you have to have the same type of problems in the military.
But you didn't have any.
I don't recall having any.
Is this, well, let's go back to what the previous question we were talking about.
The armed forces were ahead of the world in integration.
And you supported them.
Oh, I remember having, in South Carolina,
Shaw Air Force Base.
I remember having colored officers, blacks, in my outfit and sitting next to them in the officer's club dining.
And those people understood it.
They would have their fellow blacks sit at a table next to us.
There was no problem.
They understood it as well as we did, and both worked towards solving this problem.
I honestly can't remember any big flag.
I remember little bitty spats.
Oh, I remember maybe a black and an airman having a beer at the NCO because they might get in a fight.
But why wouldn't it spread with all the blacks and whites?
We never did.
I don't remember any real big promise.
So what you're saying is that with every command that you've been at,
the blacks in the command and the whites in the command that were integrated in all the time, they worked together to decrease racial tensions, or is that putting words in your mouth?
Sir, as a matter of fact, I'm aware of what you're talking about, and I gave it up to the time I got in command position.
I always gave this consideration and high priority that I went out of my way to walk across
the officer's club lounge to shake hands with a black officer and his wife.
So it ended along with my wife.
I worked at it, but I never felt any stress to have to do this.
I don't remember a problem in this area.
Great, great.
Now, as far as women, women were joining in the 1960s, especially in the 1970s.
The military passed in the never before.
We've already talked about your ideas in the draft.
Did you ever have any problems with the new
women who were coming in in the enlisted ranks or the officer ranks?
Did you have an increase, especially in the 12th when you were there?
Women, laughs.
The only problem I can remember, again, in my career with respect to women in the services, at McCord Air Force Base, when I report front of their division with my
I remember we were increasing.
As a matter of fact, when I arrived at the base, there was a barracks, a special dormitory set aside for WAFs.
And this is the first time I came up against anything like this.
This was in 1950.
Well, when I reported it to Hamlet in 1957.
Something like that.
But I'll figure something out.
If I remember correctly, there were some problems about some of the airmen.
There were some problems about some of the airmen.
Oh, it was a matter of off-limits.
That's what it was.
When I arrived, there were off-limits signs posted around the WAF barracks.
And this was the first time I'd come across any faces.
And of course, I didn't do anything about it immediately, but I wondered why and all, you know.
And it was a claim to me that the, well, you know, it was the first time I'd had anything like this.
And there's so many on this base that

sometime the airmen, you know, they'd get mixed up and the airmen would come over here and you'd get caught in the barracks and everything going on being scandalous, you know, and they had to find it off limits so that the airmen knew they'd be plenty to be came on to the dormitory.
And I was surprised to hear this.
I didn't do anything at the time, but as time went on, I think really,
I didn't do anything solid.
I think experience and time solved the problem, and these things faded away, and eventually those signs were taken down.
It wasn't an insurmountable problem.
You know, you had a little concern about it for a while, but to my knowledge, that's the only time I remember.
Oh, I remember another time when I was in Thailand.
I forget her position, but she was general, general home, HRLMS.
She was a female general in Thailand?
Right, right.
In the Air Force?
No, she was in the Air Force headquarters in personnel, but she was the head of the... One-star general?
Yeah.
I believe she was a one-star general when she came over to visit.
You know, she was making a tour in the area, just like any other staff officer from the Pentagon.
And we talked about...

women you know being introduced over there in the units in the in the combat theater and that was a problem that i'd never thought well it was a question was brought up i never thought before and uh when he brought up idea i said i don't know i have to give this some thought and we discussed it and talked about it and actually she was all for the idea see uh i didn't i didn't have a position at oh and support definitely you know and warehouse you know
Definitely not being in combat.
We weren't near that forward thing yet.
Not even she.
But I don't think the question ever was posed to me again prior to the time I rotated and came back home.
But I don't ever recall, I don't think we ever saw any women over there during the war.
But she didn't have an opinion?
I mean, you saw the pros and cons, but you didn't... At that time?
You didn't tell her?
No, no, no.

As a matter of fact, I thought about it a lot, and I thought about it a lot after that, and this is the reason I'm telling you right now, categorically, if they do go anyplace, and thinking about, based on my experience over there, they ought to be in combat roles.
I'd have been a little hard-pressed.
Kind of think about it.
Did we not put some labs in 7th Air Force Headquarters at Thompson News?
I don't know.
We may have, but that was, I don't remember specifically.
It seemed like maybe we did try that.
At any rate, not entirely.
At least when I was over there, we did.
But I'd have been reluctant.

to, even at that time, to bring women in to those air bases in South Vietnam because of the type of warfare over there where the bases could be martyred, you know, every day and overrun and actually get in hand-to-hand combat right on the base.
I'm horrified to the thought we're on a base in a WAP barracks.
It taunts a note that women be confronted in barracks with invading Vietcongs with knives in their hands.
In the end, it's expected in combat, not women.
Okay, let's ask one last question about A&M, and that is, what are your feelings toward integrating A&M?
In 1968, we left the first blacks in the A&M, and now we have
blacks equally, or not equally, but blacks going to A&M.
And this is another one of those changes during General Rutter's time as a president.
What's your idea?
What's wrong with that?
It should be done.
That's across the board in this nation.
The United States should be the forerunners in the world for human rights.
And A&M, God bless the position it is and how proud we are of it, and the
in the front ranks of supplying qualified officers and airmen to the armed forces, why not supply some qualified women to the armed forces?
Amen.
Let's go.
I'm for it.
And blacks.
And blacks, definitely.
Oh, absolutely.
And minorities, if you will.
Women and blacks, definitely.
Do you think it's a better institution today with this tremendous expansion and all of these changes in the 1960s than it was a
than it was when you went there after the Second World War?
Well, Terry, I guess, truthfully, I ought to say I'm not sure.
I'd have an opinion, but frankly, I can't answer that question, because I really don't, I haven't been on the campus of A&M in years and years.
I don't know.
But, thinking back on my experience, the bigger the outfit, the...

greater the tendency to lose supervisory control and the more care you have to give and the more careful you have to pick your key people down the line to control as you release your detailed supervision from above and get bigger you have to delegate that supervision to the lower ones and if that's

if A&M avoids these pitfalls of not, you know, delegating authority to maintain the discipline that they had when I was there, and I'm sure that it would be equal good, and I have all the confidence in the world, and I'll bet you, I'd say based on my respect for that place, that I'll bet you it's as good now as it was then.
I'd be surprised if it wasn't.
Well,
I'm out of questions.
We've talked about your career, your early years, A&M, leadership.
Is there anything for the record that you'd like to say before we close?
I mean, is there anything?
You're the expert on your life.
Is there anything that we've missed?
That we missed?
Well, I mean, any major changes or anything that you think that we should talk about?
Do you want to see the transcript?
Well, I could do that, but I could just say that if I had to do it over again, I'd do exactly what I did.
I'd go to A&M as soon as I could.
I'd get in the military as soon as I could.

become a fighter pilot as soon as I could and I'd be in a burst war as soon as I could be that we got into I'd be there and I'd strive to be promoted up the ladder and be just as ambitious as I did before I loved it then and I still think I still think that the Air Force is the greatest organization in the world I'd do it again
Well, that's an appropriate way to go.
